"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-600","children":"The interest rate is the cost of borrowing the principal alone. APR includes the interest rate plus fees, points, and other loan costs expressed as a yearly rate. APR gives a more accurate comparison of total loan cost across different lenders."}]]}],["$","details","Should I choose a 15-year or 30-year mortgage?",{"className":"rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4","children":[["$","summary",null,{"className":"cursor-pointer font-medium text-slate-900","children":"Should I choose a 15-year or 30-year mortgage?"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-600","children":"A 15-year mortgage has higher monthly payments but a significantly lower total interest cost and typically a lower interest rate. A 30-year mortgage offers lower monthly payments and more flexibility. Use the calculator to compare both scenarios with your actual numbers before deciding."}]]}],["$","details","How does this calculator handle refinancing?",{"className":"rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-4","children":[["$","summary",null,{"className":"cursor-pointer font-medium text-slate-900","children":"How does this calculator handle refinancing?"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-3 text-sm leading-6 text-slate-600","children":"Enter the remaining balance of your current loan as the principal, your new interest rate, and the new term to estimate the refinanced payment. Compare the new monthly payment and total remaining cost against continuing with your current loan to determine whether refinancing makes financial sense."}]]}]]}]]}]
